  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3730575056" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3730575056" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3730575056?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141196305" href="/book/show/10325541-chess">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=best-reviews">best-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3730575056" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5429225567279311661"><b>Chess - A Psychological Novel About National Socialism</b><br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609343016i/30613502._SX540_.jpg' width='500' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>In 1941 Stefan Zweig wrote &quot;Chess&quot; during World War II from exile in Brazil, briefly before he committed double suicide with his wife Lotte. The novel starts with an encounter between the reigning world chess champion Mirko Czentovic and the unknown Dr.B, who has the extraordinary ability to challenge the Grand Master in a game of chess. In the course of the game Dr. B‘s concealed dark and damaged past unfolds - previously driven to insanity </span>
  <span id="freeText5429225567279311661" style="display:none"><b>Chess - A Psychological Novel About National Socialism</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609343016i/30613502._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>In 1941 Stefan Zweig wrote "Chess" during World War II from exile in Brazil, briefly before he committed double suicide with his wife Lotte. The novel starts with an encounter between the reigning world chess champion Mirko Czentovic and the unknown Dr.B, who has the extraordinary ability to challenge the Grand Master in a game of chess. In the course of the game Dr. B‘s concealed dark and damaged past unfolds - previously driven to insanity during Nazi imprisonment by the chess games in his imagination.<br><br><b>Mirko Czentovic</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609343500i/30613557._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i> Mirko Czentovic - The reigning World Chess Champion and Island Genius</i><br><br>Czentovic is the reigning world chess champion. He grew up as orphaned son of labourers and was adopted by a village parson who accidentally discovers his extraordinary chess skills when Czentovic was 12. Otherwise he is extremely slow, indifferent, single-minded and limited in all intellectual domains except for chess. This makes him an unsuitable figure in the intellectual circle of elite chess players of those days. The contrast is further highlighted by the description of Czentovic’s as conceited, petty and selfish without the slightest trace of generosity or scruples. But despite his island genius at playing chess, he is unable to to imagine the chessboard layout and decide even single moves without looking at it, an ability professional chess players usually have. As a chess player Czentovic quickly came to fame but his personality is dull and his motives are shallow, power driven and monetary. <br><br><b>Dr. B.</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609342907i/30613501._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Dr. B - Imprisoned by the Nazi Regime and driven to Psychosis but Chess Genius by Solitary Confinement</i><br><br>Dr. B is the exact opposite to Mirko Czentovic, as he is cultivated, intelligent and eloquent and was born into a wealthy family. He appears as stranger, when Czentovic is beating amateur co-passengers on a cruise ship, making quick money. By intermeddling with their game, Dr. B showcases his extraordinary ability to play chess and starts to tell his story. He was imprisoned by the Gestapo (Secret State Police of the Nazi regime) and subjected to psychological torture in the form of solitary confinement, as many political prisoners were. The purpose of isolation was to eliminate all types of physical or mental stimulation so that the prisoner will be more easily manipulated into delivering or revealing information: in this case, the whereabouts of certain goods of value. During his imprisonment he realizes his mental decline in consequence of the isolation but manages to steel a book, which happens to be a collection of prominent chess games. He flees into the world of chess by laying out a chess board on his bed with bred crumbs, rebuilding and memorizing all chess games in the book. When replaying isn‘t enough cognitive stimulation anymore, he plays thousands of games against himself. He starts to develop a psychosis and symptoms of a split personality „My dreadful situation forced me at least to try splitting myself into a Black self and a White self, to keep from being crushed by the terrible void around me.“ After he is released he encounters Mirko Czentovic on board of a cruise ship, that will bring him to exile. He interferes with his chess game solely to check whether he can play a real chess game or not. He can, but his positive characteristics are his downfall: his imagination, his intelligence and his alert mind turn against him and the chess game triggers the sequence of alterations in his thought process that he experienced during his time in isolation and thereby his psychosis. In consequence Dr B. suddenly breaks off his game against Czentovic and leaves the field to him, as retreat seems to be the only solution. Symbolically, the duel between Dr. B. and Czentovic represents the struggle between culture, education, intellect and politics.<br><br><b>Extremes</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609343387i/30613550._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>An extreme lack of stimulation as well as extreme overstimulation lead to insanity</i><br><br>The novel mirrors the opposition of two worlds and two powers, as the chess game has different meanings for Dr. B and Czentovic. Czentovic is excluded from all stimulations except chess, because his mind is not able to comprehend anything else. Chess is his exceptional power and his liberation, but he is retarded in all other regards and therefore a prisoner of his own mind. For Dr. B the chess game is liberating as well but also the origin of his insanity. He tries to escape the consequences of the solitary confinement but an extreme lack of stimulation, as well as extreme overstimulation lead to the same symptoms: delirium, limited impulse control and confusion. His perception becomes affected, causing visual and auditory hallucinations, accompanied by fear and anxiety. A sympathetic doctor plays a decisive role in his release but recognizes the danger of a relapse when having future contact with the game of chess. This resembles a post-traumatic stress syndrome and could also be defined as an addiction. So while Czentovic has the ability to turn his obsession into success, it leads to Dr. B‘s downfall. But Czentovic can‘t escape or improve his narrow mindness, while Dr. B has the advantage to be able to exclude chess from his life and therefore the trigger of his insanity. He has the ability to make a choice and reflect the necessity of balance, while Czentovic can‘t. Both cases reflect how people deal with power and in both cases extremes don‘t work well.<br><br><b>Stefan Zweig</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609344612i/30613618._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Stefan Zweig (1881 - 1942)</i><br><br>Stefan Zweig wrote chess in 1941, from exile. The author was born in Austria but fled to London in 1934, ultimately exiling in Brazil, where he committed a double suicide with his wife Lotte and did not live to see the success of "Chess Story". The decision to end his life was motivated by his pessimistic view on the war and the future of Europe. Zweig‘s books were forbidden under Hitler‘s dictatorship and destroyed in the book burnings. Zweig was jewish and known for his pacifism, taking immense pleasure from intellectual creation and from his love of freedom. When that freedom was threatened, he showed great courage and coherence in going through with his elaborate suicide. Dr. B can be seen as his alter ego, as both come from affluent families and both faced persecution and envy, along with the destruction of their creations and accomplishments. Dr B. is placed in solitary confinement and Zweig was isolated by having to go into exile. Both survive, but the consequences are severe and incurable. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609343387i/30613551._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Stefan Zweig poisoned himself and his wife Lotte laid down beside him when she found his dead body </i><br><br>The contrast between different types of intelligence and different neurological symptoms are the driving force of the story, which makes the novel highly psychological. The solitary confinement described by Zweig is defined as torture, but wasn‘t systematically used by the Nazi regime. Instead the psychiatrist Albert Biderman officially introduced those methods in the CIA after the Korean War. But as the biographies of Adolf Hitler and Mirko Czentovics have quite some similarities, both are often associated or seen metaphorically. <br><br><b>
  <i>“No guilt is forgotten so long as the conscience still knows of it.”</i>
</b><br><br> "Chess" is the best novel I‘ve read with National Socialism at its core. It‘s a psychological study of characters and the consequences of obsession. In my opinion Zweig was a genius to tell a story that can be seen metaphorically in many ways, but doesn‘t have to. The element of psychosis majorly remembered me of the new Netflix series "The Queen’s Gambit" and I wonder if it was inspired by Zweig, who was extremely observant of human nature and imagined a compelling scenario that is political, psychological and philosophical. I‘m completely amazed!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5429225567279311661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

